1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:00,794
[SPEAKER_08]: Order!

2
00:00:00,814 --> 00:00:01,155
[SPEAKER_08]: Order!

3
00:00:01,195 --> 00:00:03,544
[SPEAKER_08]: You are an incorrigible delinquent at times.

4
00:00:05,853 --> 00:00:07,358
[SPEAKER_08]: Behave yourself, man!

5
00:00:20,365 --> 00:00:23,472
[SPEAKER_26]: Welcome to Manchester.

6
00:00:23,492 --> 00:00:25,155
[SPEAKER_26]: It's almost here, less than 36 hours to go.

7
00:00:25,175 --> 00:00:30,767
[SPEAKER_26]: On Thursday, it's the general election, your chance to decide on who's running the country.

8
00:00:31,268 --> 00:00:38,223
[SPEAKER_26]: And tonight, before you vote, we are here with about 80 18 to 25-year-olds to hear what's on your mind.

9
00:00:38,284 --> 00:00:40,348
[SPEAKER_26]: Tonight, it's all about you.

10
00:00:42,404 --> 00:00:46,476
[SPEAKER_13]: Hi there, I'm Giles and one of my friends was taken in the Manchester attack.

11
00:00:46,997 --> 00:00:54,017
[SPEAKER_13]: My question to the candidates is if they find it morally just to use terror attack victims for their own political ends.

12
00:00:54,757 --> 00:00:56,099
[SPEAKER_02]: Hi, I'm Tash from London.

13
00:00:56,400 --> 00:00:58,043
[SPEAKER_02]: My biggest concern is the NHS.

14
00:00:58,404 --> 00:01:00,147
[SPEAKER_02]: How will the government continue to fund it?

15
00:01:00,527 --> 00:01:04,555
[SPEAKER_02]: And how will wait times for appointments and surgery be reduced for those desperately in need?

16
00:01:04,615 --> 00:01:06,799
[SPEAKER_26]: OK, plenty more from these guys tonight.

17
00:01:06,839 --> 00:01:13,891
[SPEAKER_26]: We are also joined by senior politicians from seven parties who will be listening and responding to what everyone's got to say.

18
00:01:13,932 --> 00:01:17,558
[SPEAKER_26]: They are Nadeem Zahawi for the Conservatives,

19
00:01:17,538 --> 00:01:19,943
[SPEAKER_26]: representing Labour, Sarah Champion.

20
00:01:19,963 --> 00:01:23,129
[SPEAKER_26]: Kate Forbes is here for the Scottish National Party.

21
00:01:23,690 --> 00:01:25,573
[SPEAKER_26]: David Curtin is from UKIP.

22
00:01:25,954 --> 00:01:28,379
[SPEAKER_26]: Brian Paddock is from the Liberal Democrats.

23
00:01:28,980 --> 00:01:31,625
[SPEAKER_26]: Fleur Elin for Plaid Cymru joins us.

24
00:01:31,645 --> 00:01:35,091
[SPEAKER_26]: And for the Green Party, their co-leader, Jonathan Bartley.

25
00:01:35,813 --> 00:01:36,294
[SPEAKER_26]: Also...

26
00:01:38,458 --> 00:01:38,618
[SPEAKER_26]: APPLAUSE

27
00:01:43,103 --> 00:01:54,345
[SPEAKER_26]: Also, Newspeak's Jonathan Blake is working with BBC Reality Check tonight, looking at some of the numbers and some of the promises we will hear about tonight, working out what really stacks up.

28
00:01:54,505 --> 00:02:01,939
[SPEAKER_26]: And Nick Rotherham is up there going through the comments we've been getting all day at hashtag BBC debate.

29
00:02:05,513 --> 00:02:20,923
[SPEAKER_26]: First, tonight, after two devastating terror attacks in just two weeks, including one here in Manchester, security has become a much bigger part of the election campaign, in particular, how best to protect British people from any future attacks.

30
00:02:22,557 --> 00:02:27,564
[SPEAKER_08]: Police numbers in England and Wales have fallen by almost 20,000 since 2010.

31
00:02:27,644 --> 00:02:35,254
[SPEAKER_08]: Numbers have gone down in Northern Ireland too, although in Scotland they've been more or less increasing for the last 30 years.

32
00:02:36,075 --> 00:02:48,531
[SPEAKER_08]: Police budgets in England and Wales were reduced by almost a fifth between 2010 and 2015, but since then they've been protected and counter-terrorism funding has been rising with inflation.

33
00:02:48,511 --> 00:02:52,957
[SPEAKER_08]: Since 2000, various governments have introduced nine anti-terror laws.

34
00:02:53,538 --> 00:03:00,568
[SPEAKER_08]: They include the ability to stop terrorism suspects from re-entering the UK and keeping people deemed a threat under house arrest.

35
00:03:01,188 --> 00:03:07,397
[SPEAKER_08]: The current terrorism threat level is at severe, meaning an attack is highly likely.

36
00:03:07,377 --> 00:03:11,223
[SPEAKER_08]: There have been three attacks in the UK in the last 77 days.

37
00:03:11,784 --> 00:03:18,576
[SPEAKER_08]: Though the Home Office say intelligence services have prevented another five since the attack on Westminster in March.

38
00:03:19,698 --> 00:03:23,504
[SPEAKER_26]: OK, let's get your thoughts on the best way to protect British people.

39
00:03:23,524 --> 00:03:24,205
[SPEAKER_26]: Hello.

40
00:03:24,252 --> 00:03:27,196
[SPEAKER_23]: Hello, my name is Benjamin Shotton and I'm 18 from Cheshire.

41
00:03:28,619 --> 00:03:39,075
[SPEAKER_23]: Across the wake of these terror attacks, I've found that the dialogue has been very much about unity between different political parties and people from all different kinds of walks of life all over the world.

42
00:03:39,836 --> 00:03:45,965
[SPEAKER_23]: Why is it that the Conservative Party has been so divisive by saying enough is enough and that we're being too soft on terror?

43
00:03:46,506 --> 00:03:47,708
[SPEAKER_26]: Okay, we'll put that to them.

44
00:03:48,148 --> 00:03:49,230
[SPEAKER_16]: Some more of your comments?

45
00:03:50,830 --> 00:03:53,576
[SPEAKER_16]: I'm Jessica and I'm from, I live in Liverpool, but I'm from Flint.

46
00:03:54,077 --> 00:04:02,233
[SPEAKER_16]: And I want to know what we're going to do to stop terrorist attacks happening in the first place, instead of worrying about how many police you've got on the streets to deal with it when it's happening.

47
00:04:02,814 --> 00:04:05,980
[SPEAKER_16]: I understand the Conservatives want to introduce new terror offences.

48
00:04:06,421 --> 00:04:07,363
[SPEAKER_16]: What else is going to be done?

49
00:04:07,584 --> 00:04:12,754
[SPEAKER_16]: Because we always hear that, or they're known, they're on the watch list, either in this country or elsewhere.

50
00:04:13,122 --> 00:04:16,046
[SPEAKER_16]: So what are we going to do to tackle extremism in the first place?

51
00:04:16,066 --> 00:04:16,367
[SPEAKER_16]: OK.

52
00:04:16,587 --> 00:04:16,947
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you.

53
00:04:16,968 --> 00:04:17,128
[SPEAKER_16]: Hello.

54
00:04:17,388 --> 00:04:18,209
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm Tom.

55
00:04:18,370 --> 00:04:18,790
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm 22.

56
00:04:19,251 --> 00:04:22,315
[SPEAKER_03]: I actually live across from Manchester Arena and didn't get much sleep on the night of the attack.

57
00:04:22,816 --> 00:04:26,541
[SPEAKER_03]: And for me, my biggest problem is that I went to the One Love Manchester concert as well.

58
00:04:26,581 --> 00:04:33,031
[SPEAKER_03]: And at a time when, you know, Manchester and the UK is coming together, it seems like Westminster's just intent on tearing itself apart.

59
00:04:33,451 --> 00:04:38,218
[SPEAKER_03]: So what tonight are we going to see from you guys in terms of real solution instead of playing the blame game?

60
00:04:38,468 --> 00:04:40,970
[SPEAKER_26]: OK, Nadeem Zahawi from the Conservatives.

61
00:04:41,011 --> 00:04:43,033
[SPEAKER_26]: What's Tom going to see tonight from you?

62
00:04:43,733 --> 00:04:46,616
[SPEAKER_09]: I'm going to try to cover all three comments.

63
00:04:48,358 --> 00:04:49,679
[SPEAKER_09]: I came to this country in 1978.

64
00:04:49,739 --> 00:04:51,241
[SPEAKER_09]: I was about 11 years old.

65
00:04:51,321 --> 00:04:52,142
[SPEAKER_09]: I couldn't speak English.

66
00:04:52,222 --> 00:04:58,107
[SPEAKER_09]: My parents had to flee Iraq from a dictator, actually not too dissimilar to Abdi's parents.

67
00:04:58,688 --> 00:05:03,293
[SPEAKER_09]: The difference is my parents embraced the country that rescued them, and we integrated.

68
00:05:03,713 --> 00:05:05,775
[SPEAKER_09]: I learned English within six months.

69
00:05:05,755 --> 00:05:14,290
[SPEAKER_09]: I went to university, I've built a great business, I'm now the member, well I used to be, I'm the candidate now, I was the member of parliament for Stratford-on-Avon, the heart of England.

70
00:05:15,372 --> 00:05:22,785
[SPEAKER_09]: This country is a great country, it has incredible values, values of freedom, opportunity, democracy, rule of law, tolerance.

71
00:05:22,765 --> 00:05:42,086
[SPEAKER_09]: I think one of the things that we have not done well is integration, but also we've for too long tolerated people who preached extremism and hatred amongst us, people who preached intolerance to our values, to our way of life, misogyny, all sorts of things.

72
00:05:42,106 --> 00:05:45,350
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think we've got to call those people out in our communities.

73
00:05:45,370 --> 00:05:48,553
[SPEAKER_09]: And I think the Muslim community, the mainstream Muslim community,

74
00:05:48,533 --> 00:06:04,062
[SPEAKER_09]: is equally targeted by these extremists, by these criminals, because they target Ahmadiyya Muslims or other Muslims as well as being kuffar, which is people who are outside the religion, therefore easy game in many ways.

75
00:06:04,042 --> 00:06:11,734
[SPEAKER_09]: But what we've got to do is come together as political parties, as a community, and call out intolerance and say, that's wrong.

76
00:06:12,155 --> 00:06:13,757
[SPEAKER_09]: Our society is not like that.

77
00:06:13,777 --> 00:06:14,739
[SPEAKER_09]: We're proud of what we are.

78
00:06:14,959 --> 00:06:19,146
[SPEAKER_09]: What Manchester did at the concert was incredible, truly incredible.

79
00:06:19,526 --> 00:06:24,574
[SPEAKER_09]: And that should be our role model in many ways of how we deal with this as a political party.

80
00:06:24,594 --> 00:06:25,596
[SPEAKER_09]: I'd like us to come together.

81
00:06:25,976 --> 00:06:27,619
[SPEAKER_09]: Let's not keep

82
00:06:28,240 --> 00:06:30,424
[SPEAKER_09]: We're tearing chunks out of one another.

83
00:06:30,444 --> 00:06:35,392
[SPEAKER_09]: Let's say, look, how can we work together to get the right legislation through Parliament so that we can do this?

84
00:06:35,412 --> 00:06:36,534
[SPEAKER_09]: But it's not just legislation.

85
00:06:36,955 --> 00:06:40,822
[SPEAKER_09]: It's also, how do we come together and call out these extremists?

86
00:06:41,203 --> 00:06:49,557
[SPEAKER_26]: Tom, can you maybe give Nadim some more detail about the types of things, the conversation that politicians are having that you don't like, that switches you off?

87
00:06:49,705 --> 00:06:55,751
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, for me, it's just the aggressive nature of how politics has become, especially seeing Prime Minister's questions, seeing you guys at debates.

88
00:06:55,811 --> 00:06:59,915
[SPEAKER_03]: I watched the leaders' debate on TV last week, and it was just a complete noise and a faff.

89
00:06:59,995 --> 00:07:02,958
[SPEAKER_03]: And what I see now is that translates into social media.

90
00:07:03,558 --> 00:07:06,361
[SPEAKER_03]: And for us as young people, we use social media all the time.

91
00:07:06,401 --> 00:07:08,002
[SPEAKER_03]: We're on Facebook, Twitter, Instagram.

92
00:07:08,363 --> 00:07:18,312
[SPEAKER_03]: And the moment that someone puts a political point of view on Facebook or Twitter, we get the same kind of aggressive comments that you guys seem to be throwing back at each other, especially Labour and the Conservatives.

93
00:07:18,292 --> 00:07:23,388
[SPEAKER_03]: And one thing that we have seen recently is Labour pointing the finger at Theresa May and saying, this is your fault.

94
00:07:23,568 --> 00:07:25,715
[SPEAKER_03]: These people died because of you as Home Secretary.

95
00:07:26,056 --> 00:07:28,082
[SPEAKER_03]: That's just not right to blame one single person.

96
00:07:29,092 --> 00:07:31,015
[SPEAKER_09]: Look, and I agree with you.

97
00:07:31,175 --> 00:07:34,560
[SPEAKER_09]: It isn't right, and I think we should try and just pull back from that.

98
00:07:34,961 --> 00:07:43,354
[SPEAKER_09]: The one thing I would say to you is the bit that you see on Wednesday afternoon, which is sort of the Prime Minister's question time, is not what we do.

99
00:07:43,494 --> 00:07:53,850
[SPEAKER_09]: So if you look at the committee stage of any bill, or the Foreign Affairs Committee, which I sat on, where we got a fantastic report into the intervention in Libya,

100
00:07:53,830 --> 00:08:00,182
[SPEAKER_09]: which has been cited, in fact, on many news programs during the election campaign, as being a really good report.

101
00:08:00,202 --> 00:08:01,624
[SPEAKER_09]: And that was cross-party.

102
00:08:01,704 --> 00:08:03,968
[SPEAKER_09]: We worked together in those committees.

103
00:08:04,069 --> 00:08:05,912
[SPEAKER_09]: And that work is the real work of Parliament.

104
00:08:06,393 --> 00:08:08,737
[SPEAKER_09]: And I hope that young people get to see some of that.

105
00:08:08,757 --> 00:08:16,952
[SPEAKER_09]: Sadly, most of it takes place in the background rather than, as you say, the sort of the yaboo bits of politics.

106
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:18,202
[SPEAKER_26]: Sarah Champion from Labour.

107
00:08:18,622 --> 00:08:18,903
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you.

108
00:08:18,923 --> 00:08:21,026
[SPEAKER_21]: First of all, I have to defend my party.

109
00:08:21,066 --> 00:08:24,891
[SPEAKER_21]: We very, very deliberately throughout this campaign have not done the smearing.

110
00:08:24,971 --> 00:08:26,534
[SPEAKER_21]: We've not done the name calling.

111
00:08:26,554 --> 00:08:35,607
[SPEAKER_21]: And so what you're saying about Theresa May, what we're doing is we're looking at her record over the last seven years, six of which she was the Home Secretary, so in charge of police, in charge of our security.

112
00:08:35,967 --> 00:08:40,814
[SPEAKER_21]: And I think it's acceptable to look at policies and look at decisions that politicians make.

113
00:08:41,095 --> 00:08:44,239
[SPEAKER_21]: But I completely agree, it's totally unacceptable to name call.

114
00:08:44,219 --> 00:08:58,577
[SPEAKER_21]: To go back to the bigger picture, I would say in the last five years, it's become much more acceptable to use really despicable language, which I would actually say is getting very close to hate crimes on social media.

115
00:08:58,798 --> 00:09:01,381
[SPEAKER_21]: Politicians are using it, posters that we're seeing.

116
00:09:01,401 --> 00:09:05,506
[SPEAKER_21]: I have to say the Brexit campaign was a particularly vile example of that.

117
00:09:06,267 --> 00:09:12,555
[SPEAKER_21]: I'm glad that it feels in this election that that's calmed a little bit, but we need to have zero tolerance to that sort of thing.

118
00:09:12,535 --> 00:09:21,255
[SPEAKER_21]: To look at the big picture, it's not just about a knee-jerk reaction of bringing in more police, bringing in more legislation.

119
00:09:21,656 --> 00:09:29,093
[SPEAKER_21]: What we need to be doing is, from the youngest age, is teaching people about respect, about tolerance, and embedding that in.

120
00:09:29,073 --> 00:09:31,238
[SPEAKER_21]: and then bringing back things like the youth service.

121
00:09:31,258 --> 00:09:33,983
[SPEAKER_21]: You know, the youth service has been decimated in the last seven years.

122
00:09:34,324 --> 00:09:43,163
[SPEAKER_21]: That's the place where young people can be, you know, just sort of channeled a little bit if they're saying things which are too upsetting, controversial, radical.

123
00:09:43,924 --> 00:09:45,127
[SPEAKER_21]: That system isn't there now.

124
00:09:45,207 --> 00:09:46,069
[SPEAKER_21]: So we're seeing

125
00:09:46,049 --> 00:09:52,177
[SPEAKER_21]: that the schools are under-resourced, we're seeing the youth services disappeared, we're seeing the police, the community police aren't there.

126
00:09:52,617 --> 00:10:00,207
[SPEAKER_21]: So all of those levels, which would have been like our canaries, when things were starting to go wrong, we could have gone, oops, hang on, we've got an issue here, let's put some support around that person.

127
00:10:00,548 --> 00:10:14,065
[SPEAKER_21]: With all that gone, it becomes an inevitability that it's only when someone does something so utterly despicable, and I'm really sorry for the people that are directly impacted on what's happened in these last three, actually, atrocities.

128
00:10:14,045 --> 00:10:16,010
[SPEAKER_21]: We shouldn't just be waiting until that moment.

129
00:10:16,030 --> 00:10:18,616
[SPEAKER_21]: We should be doing something decades before.

130
00:10:19,218 --> 00:10:26,515
[SPEAKER_26]: OK, let's get some more of your thoughts.

131
00:10:26,535 --> 00:10:28,881
[SPEAKER_20]: Who else wants to make a comment?

132
00:10:29,603 --> 00:10:33,908
[SPEAKER_20]: Hi, I'm Claire from Manchester, and I have a question for everybody.

133
00:10:34,869 --> 00:10:40,394
[SPEAKER_20]: So obviously after the recent horrible attacks, I have seen a lot more armed police around.

134
00:10:41,035 --> 00:10:47,662
[SPEAKER_20]: Is that something that you guys would look at kind of installing permanently, or what's everybody's specific view on that?

135
00:10:47,682 --> 00:10:51,446
[SPEAKER_26]: Okay, Brian Paddock, you have experience as a retired police officer.

136
00:10:51,606 --> 00:10:52,387
[SPEAKER_26]: What would you do?

137
00:10:52,467 --> 00:10:57,012
[SPEAKER_26]: You want to put more money, we know, into local police, but would that be armed police?

138
00:10:57,532 --> 00:11:06,486
[SPEAKER_06]: No, I mean, there are two issues here, and it's not about... You've got to have the police there to respond, as you said, when an incident like this happens.

139
00:11:07,106 --> 00:11:15,439
[SPEAKER_06]: And luckily in London, there was a great number of armed response vehicles, they're called, who were able to respond really quickly to deal with the incident.

140
00:11:15,419 --> 00:11:23,741
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm a bit concerned that in other parts of the country there might not be enough armed officers because there's like a thousand less than there were 10 years ago.

141
00:11:23,761 --> 00:11:26,408
[SPEAKER_06]: A thousand less armed officers than there were 10 years ago.

142
00:11:26,748 --> 00:11:28,292
[SPEAKER_06]: So that's one aspect of it.

143
00:11:28,313 --> 00:11:31,200
[SPEAKER_06]: But the most important aspect as far as we're concerned is

144
00:11:31,180 --> 00:11:34,547
[SPEAKER_06]: is this erosion of community policing.

145
00:11:34,827 --> 00:11:43,865
[SPEAKER_06]: Because as well as the 20,000 police officers that we've lost since 2010, we've also lost 24,000 support officers.

146
00:11:44,125 --> 00:11:49,476
[SPEAKER_06]: And the police community support officers are a big part of those community teams.

147
00:11:49,456 --> 00:11:57,855
[SPEAKER_06]: And what that means is that some communities begin to lose trust and confidence in the police because they don't have a local officer that they can relate to.

148
00:11:58,417 --> 00:12:01,303
[SPEAKER_06]: And when that happens, it means that you don't get the intelligence.

149
00:12:01,323 --> 00:12:07,397
[SPEAKER_06]: I don't know whether people saw the reports the day after the London Bridge attack.

150
00:12:07,377 --> 00:12:17,254
[SPEAKER_06]: One of the neighbours of one of the guys involved said, oh, I remember now, earlier on, on the Saturday, he was being over-friendly, and then he started talking to me about hiring a van.

151
00:12:17,695 --> 00:12:18,857
[SPEAKER_06]: Of course, it now all makes sense.

152
00:12:18,917 --> 00:12:28,474
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, maybe if he'd had his suspicions about that guy, there'd been local community officers that he could have talked to, maybe he might have talked to them about his feelings.

153
00:12:28,454 --> 00:12:36,526
[SPEAKER_06]: We know that that guy was already on the radar of the security services, so maybe the security services might have put two and two together.

154
00:12:36,847 --> 00:12:39,951
[SPEAKER_06]: So we don't think we need more powers.

155
00:12:39,971 --> 00:12:41,894
[SPEAKER_06]: We don't think we need more draconian powers.

156
00:12:42,255 --> 00:12:50,968
[SPEAKER_06]: There's lots of powers that the police and the security services have that they're not using at the moment, but we need to make sure that they use them effectively.

157
00:12:50,999 --> 00:12:52,903
[SPEAKER_19]: Okay, lady here in the front row, hello.

158
00:12:53,304 --> 00:12:55,689
[SPEAKER_19]: My name is Maria, I'm 21, I'm from Manchester.

159
00:12:56,691 --> 00:13:09,598
[SPEAKER_19]: Just going off of what you were saying and what you were just saying just now, due to the colour of my skin in the wake of the awful terror attacks that have just happened in Manchester, I am genuinely afraid to go out to the city, my city,

160
00:13:09,578 --> 00:13:11,120
[SPEAKER_19]: It has been my home for countless years.

161
00:13:14,004 --> 00:13:32,151
[SPEAKER_19]: Mostly afraid of hate attacks, not even terrorist attacks, from people not knowing, maybe even young people, not just online, but actually being in public, I take the tram to uni, I'm afraid to take the tram now, just afraid that someone might say something to you and you don't want to engage in conflict or confrontation.

162
00:13:32,171 --> 00:13:38,640
[SPEAKER_19]: What are the different political parties, what are they doing about this now?

163
00:13:38,620 --> 00:13:42,405
[SPEAKER_06]: Some of it has got to be about understanding what is going on here.

164
00:13:42,705 --> 00:13:55,583
[SPEAKER_06]: These people who are carrying out these terrorist attacks, they believe in a violent political ideology that wants to overthrow democracy, that wants to overthrow our liberal values.

165
00:13:56,123 --> 00:13:59,548
[SPEAKER_06]: That is completely different from the Muslim religion.

166
00:13:59,528 --> 00:14:02,151
[SPEAKER_06]: Muslim religion isn't about overthrowing democracy.

167
00:14:02,211 --> 00:14:08,498
[SPEAKER_06]: Muslim religion is, you know, is about worshipping Allah and living a good life and so forth.

168
00:14:08,518 --> 00:14:22,935
[SPEAKER_06]: And so part of it, you know, we've had instances in the past where people following an Islamist attack, you know, this violent political ideology, people have started attacking Sikh good warriors because they don't even know the difference between Muslims and Sikhs.

169
00:14:23,375 --> 00:14:27,460
[SPEAKER_06]: So we've got to clamp down on all sorts of hate crime.

170
00:14:27,440 --> 00:14:30,144
[SPEAKER_26]: Let me bring in David Curtin from UKIP.

171
00:14:30,184 --> 00:14:33,609
[SPEAKER_26]: How do you respond to this lady here and her fears about hate crime?

