858
01:10:00,583 --> 01:10:09,918
[SPEAKER_12]: It's a handout to corporations to give them a workforce which they can employ in minimum wage jobs for less than minimum wage and give them no skills.

859
01:10:10,699 --> 01:10:13,924
[SPEAKER_12]: So how do you plan to tackle these exploitative apprenticeships?

860
01:10:14,292 --> 01:10:18,480
[SPEAKER_26]: OK, let's welcome you down here.

861
01:10:18,500 --> 01:10:18,661
[SPEAKER_26]: Hi.

862
01:10:19,823 --> 01:10:20,144
[SPEAKER_26]: Hello.

863
01:10:20,424 --> 01:10:21,546
[SPEAKER_26]: Yeah, your time.

864
01:10:21,566 --> 01:10:22,969
[SPEAKER_31]: My name's Colin, I'm 21, I'm from Glasgow.

865
01:10:23,530 --> 01:10:27,498
[SPEAKER_31]: Funny you said that, the apprenticeship, I actually finished myself a government-funded apprenticeship.

866
01:10:28,019 --> 01:10:35,895
[SPEAKER_31]: But I'm actually recently unemployed, so what I was wondering, a question to all parties, maybe more specifically the SNP, but what will you do to create more jobs for people our age?

867
01:10:35,875 --> 01:10:37,257
[SPEAKER_26]: Tell me about your apprenticeship.

868
01:10:37,277 --> 01:10:38,259
[SPEAKER_31]: What were you doing?

869
01:10:38,279 --> 01:10:45,269
[SPEAKER_31]: The one I'd done was actually digital marketing, like IT and admin, but it was more like what he was covering.

870
01:10:45,289 --> 01:10:48,895
[SPEAKER_31]: It was more of a sales role where I was on the phone and speaking to customers and stuff like that.

871
01:10:48,915 --> 01:10:49,315
[SPEAKER_26]: How did you find it?

872
01:10:49,335 --> 01:10:49,956
[SPEAKER_26]: Was it useful?

873
01:10:49,976 --> 01:10:50,978
[SPEAKER_26]: What were you getting paid?

874
01:10:50,998 --> 01:10:52,941
[SPEAKER_31]: Yeah, well, I learned a lot of work skills, obviously.

875
01:10:52,961 --> 01:10:56,586
[SPEAKER_31]: I learned a lot more about being in a workforce and being responsible and stuff like that.

876
01:10:56,606 --> 01:11:04,498
[SPEAKER_31]: But in terms of going from that into another job, which was initially, I was told that that would be a high likability.

877
01:11:04,478 --> 01:11:09,445
[SPEAKER_31]: the high probability of that being, I didn't actually come into employment after it.

878
01:11:09,466 --> 01:11:17,758
[SPEAKER_31]: So I did learn a lot, but I don't think it's, the way it's made out as if it's a stepping stone to getting straight into work, I don't think that's always the case.

879
01:11:17,778 --> 01:11:19,020
[SPEAKER_30]: Okay, Kate Forbes, SMB?

880
01:11:19,360 --> 01:11:28,795
[SPEAKER_30]: Yeah, well, I think if you ever wanted an example of how austerity hasn't worked for the last seven years, employment and youth employment is a good place to start.

881
01:11:29,275 --> 01:11:33,642
[SPEAKER_30]: And the Conservatives like to style themselves as looking after the economy and meeting these

882
01:11:33,622 --> 01:11:37,128
[SPEAKER_30]: financial targets, and yet they've singularly failed to do that.

883
01:11:37,629 --> 01:11:40,775
[SPEAKER_30]: And so the economy has not grown at the extent it should have.

884
01:11:41,216 --> 01:11:47,126
[SPEAKER_30]: And austerity has actually kept the economy back, which means you haven't got the same extent of job creation.

885
01:11:47,527 --> 01:11:49,150
[SPEAKER_30]: But it isn't just about

886
01:11:49,130 --> 01:11:50,172
[SPEAKER_30]: people in employment.

887
01:11:50,312 --> 01:11:51,995
[SPEAKER_30]: It's about what they're getting paid as well.

888
01:11:52,496 --> 01:11:57,624
[SPEAKER_30]: And again, we in the SNP feel very, very strongly that people should be paid a fair wage.

889
01:11:57,644 --> 01:12:01,791
[SPEAKER_30]: They should be paid the real living wage, not the rebranded living wage.

890
01:12:02,392 --> 01:12:05,598
[SPEAKER_30]: And the cutoff should not be age 25.

891
01:12:05,718 --> 01:12:13,551
[SPEAKER_30]: Why should somebody age 26 earn something that's a different wage from somebody age 24 who might be doing exactly the same job?

892
01:12:13,531 --> 01:12:24,505
[SPEAKER_30]: So we've said in our manifesto that we're committed to raising the minimum wage in line with the real living wage so that it's over £10 over the next parliamentary term.

893
01:12:25,086 --> 01:12:39,184
[SPEAKER_30]: But it really does come back to ending austerity, making sure that people have money in their pockets that they can spend so there's more money going round the economy and that means that our economy grows, we're more productive and it's better all round.

894
01:12:39,164 --> 01:12:41,329
[SPEAKER_26]: Nadine Zahawi, Conservatives.

895
01:12:41,389 --> 01:12:43,093
[SPEAKER_26]: We heard about zero-hours contracts.

896
01:12:43,113 --> 01:12:52,655
[SPEAKER_26]: More people are in work, but a lot of that work is low-paid, low-hours, insecure, and disproportionately affects young people when it comes to zero-hour contracts.

897
01:12:52,675 --> 01:12:53,798
[SPEAKER_26]: What would you do for them?

898
01:12:54,048 --> 01:12:57,032
[SPEAKER_09]: Well, first of all, we introduced the National Living Wage.

899
01:12:57,052 --> 01:12:59,296
[SPEAKER_09]: The Conservative Chancellor did that at £7.50.

900
01:12:59,716 --> 01:13:07,007
[SPEAKER_09]: We've pledged to increase that to 60% of median wage and then continue for it to go up with inflation.

901
01:13:07,788 --> 01:13:14,638
[SPEAKER_09]: I spent a year as the Prime Minister's Apprenticeship Advisor when David Cameron introduced the Apprenticeship Programme where

902
01:13:14,618 --> 01:13:20,226
[SPEAKER_09]: we're basically putting a levy, half a percent of the wage bill of very large corporations.

903
01:13:20,246 --> 01:13:26,194
[SPEAKER_09]: So any company that has a wage bill of three million pounds, half a percent of that is taken in apprenticeship levy.

904
01:13:26,255 --> 01:13:32,263
[SPEAKER_09]: So that's basically going to deliver about three billion pounds of investment into apprenticeships.

905
01:13:32,363 --> 01:13:35,007
[SPEAKER_09]: Now, when I looked at this,

906
01:13:35,307 --> 01:13:38,250
[SPEAKER_09]: The Americans emailed, said, look, can we come and have a look at what you've done?

907
01:13:38,550 --> 01:13:42,835
[SPEAKER_09]: Because we delivered about 2 million apprenticeships in the five years when David Cameron was prime minister.

908
01:13:42,855 --> 01:13:46,459
[SPEAKER_09]: And then we set a target of 3 million for this parliament as well.

909
01:13:47,880 --> 01:13:49,062
[SPEAKER_09]: We were doing something good, yes.

910
01:13:49,102 --> 01:13:51,064
[SPEAKER_09]: It could always get better, I think.

911
01:13:51,164 --> 01:13:55,989
[SPEAKER_09]: And degree apprenticeships, for example, are something that really is pioneering.

912
01:13:56,049 --> 01:13:59,653
[SPEAKER_09]: So a teaching assistant can become a teacher on a degree apprenticeship.

913
01:13:59,853 --> 01:14:02,496
[SPEAKER_09]: A nursing assistant can become a nurse on a degree apprenticeship.

914
01:14:02,476 --> 01:14:05,399
[SPEAKER_09]: and be paid as well as getting that degree apprenticeship.

915
01:14:06,681 --> 01:14:15,390
[SPEAKER_09]: But when you look at countries like Germany, one of the sort of insights that I took from that is that in Germany, businesses were embedded in the education system.

916
01:14:15,470 --> 01:14:22,978
[SPEAKER_09]: So every child had exposure to both the opportunity of going to university or going on an apprenticeship.

917
01:14:23,479 --> 01:14:25,381
[SPEAKER_09]: And the system was pretty stable.

918
01:14:25,421 --> 01:14:30,947
[SPEAKER_09]: And I'm glad that actually Labour worked with us very much on the apprenticeship levy and support the apprenticeship levy

919
01:14:30,927 --> 01:14:31,468
[SPEAKER_09]: on this.

920
01:14:32,670 --> 01:14:43,331
[SPEAKER_09]: On zero-hours contracts, which I think you mentioned, so the problem with zero-hours contracts when we came into office is an employer can say, right, you're on zero-hours contracts and you're exclusive to me.

921
01:14:43,371 --> 01:14:44,153
[SPEAKER_09]: You can't go anywhere else.

922
01:14:44,173 --> 01:14:47,239
[SPEAKER_09]: You've got to sit at home, wait by the phone until I ring you.

923
01:14:47,940 --> 01:14:51,186
[SPEAKER_09]: What we did was we changed the legislation to say, no, it should be equal.

924
01:14:51,226 --> 01:14:52,108
[SPEAKER_09]: If you want

925
01:14:52,088 --> 01:14:56,234
[SPEAKER_09]: me to give you my time, I should be able to go to three, four employers.

926
01:14:56,294 --> 01:14:59,739
[SPEAKER_06]: It was Liberal Democrats in the coalition who pushed that, and the Tories resisted it.

927
01:14:59,799 --> 01:15:00,560
[SPEAKER_06]: Let me just finish.

928
01:15:00,680 --> 01:15:02,002
[SPEAKER_09]: You have your chance to speak.

929
01:15:02,303 --> 01:15:02,723
[SPEAKER_09]: Relax.

930
01:15:03,705 --> 01:15:08,752
[SPEAKER_09]: So we introduced the idea of actually both ways.

931
01:15:08,792 --> 01:15:15,261
[SPEAKER_09]: The employee can decide to have three, four, five different contracts with different employers, and they can choose.

932
01:15:15,241 --> 01:15:22,909
[SPEAKER_09]: There was a really interesting piece of work that McDonald's did the other day, and our fact checker hopefully will support me on this.

933
01:15:23,249 --> 01:15:28,614
[SPEAKER_09]: So they offered all their zero-hours contract employees to go on a permanent contract.

934
01:15:29,375 --> 01:15:31,917
[SPEAKER_09]: 80% of them said, no, we don't want to go on a permanent contract.

935
01:15:31,978 --> 01:15:37,883
[SPEAKER_09]: We prefer the flexibility, whether they were students or for whatever reason, they wanted that flexibility.

936
01:15:38,304 --> 01:15:44,590
[SPEAKER_09]: So we have to be careful before we sort of tar a hole.

937
01:15:44,570 --> 01:15:47,955
[SPEAKER_09]: section of the workforce by saying, actually, you know what, these are all bad.

938
01:15:48,015 --> 01:15:54,205
[SPEAKER_09]: Actually, people sometimes prefer that flexibility, especially if they're studying and want to work at certain hours, not all the time.

939
01:15:54,406 --> 01:15:55,768
[SPEAKER_26]: Brian Paddock, Liberal Democrats.

940
01:15:55,908 --> 01:16:01,797
[SPEAKER_06]: So 40% of people who do zero-hours contracts want to continue to do zero-hours contracts.

941
01:16:02,118 --> 01:16:07,827
[SPEAKER_06]: But what we want to make sure is that that isn't used as a way of exploiting people.

942
01:16:07,807 --> 01:16:16,280
[SPEAKER_06]: So if people are actually working regular hours, there should be a legal right for those people to move on to a fixed contract rather than zero-hours contracts.

943
01:16:16,661 --> 01:16:22,750
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm afraid taking the minimum wage and just recalling it the living wage does not make it a living wage.

944
01:16:28,198 --> 01:16:31,924
[SPEAKER_26]: Has anyone here had a zero-hours contract?

945
01:16:32,343 --> 01:16:34,506
[SPEAKER_26]: OK, let's get some microphones to you.

946
01:16:34,526 --> 01:16:34,846
[SPEAKER_26]: Hello.

947
01:16:35,267 --> 01:16:38,652
[SPEAKER_24]: Hi, my name's Rachel and I'm from Inverness in the Scottish Highlands.

948
01:16:39,413 --> 01:16:44,940
[SPEAKER_24]: I am on a zero-hour contract, but my company calls it a relief contract, just because it's not as scary.

949
01:16:46,062 --> 01:16:55,735
[SPEAKER_24]: But I'm a youth worker for my local authority, and as Kate has previously mentioned, my budget comes from my local authority, which comes from Holyrood, which comes from Westminster.

950
01:16:56,356 --> 01:17:00,983
[SPEAKER_24]: Now if there are more cuts made to the budget, my job's on the firing line.

951
01:17:01,464 --> 01:17:11,899
[SPEAKER_24]: Now we've been extremely lucky in Highland that we've had our internal budgets cut, which I can't believe I'm saying this, only means that the projects that I do with young people are being cut.

952
01:17:11,919 --> 01:17:14,103
[SPEAKER_24]: My job is not on the line yet.

953
01:17:14,123 --> 01:17:20,372
[SPEAKER_24]: My job involves working with young people and giving them the benchmark to their future.

954
01:17:20,352 --> 01:17:35,186
[SPEAKER_24]: If our budgets are being cut in Westminster and that path follows me to the Highland Council, how on earth am I going to prepare the next generation of young people, the next generation of your electorate, to be skilled for the jobs of five years' time?

955
01:17:35,647 --> 01:17:36,249
[SPEAKER_24]: Thank you.

956
01:17:37,331 --> 01:17:38,935
[SPEAKER_24]: Who else is on a zero-hours contract?

957
01:17:39,927 --> 01:17:45,837
[SPEAKER_02]: I've been on a zero-hours contract since I was about 17 and I've always really enjoyed being on it because it gives me flexibility.

958
01:17:46,057 --> 01:17:47,359
[SPEAKER_02]: What do you do?

959
01:17:47,379 --> 01:17:49,683
[SPEAKER_02]: I work in retail and do promo jobs as well.

960
01:17:50,865 --> 01:17:55,693
[SPEAKER_02]: But I think the question should be more about what the minimum wage should be in terms of long-term contracts.

961
01:17:55,793 --> 01:18:03,166
[SPEAKER_02]: I've just finished uni and I'm looking for jobs in London, but how am I expected to get a job when some of them are paying £16,000 a year?

962
01:18:03,346 --> 01:18:04,568
[SPEAKER_02]: How am I also going to pay for

963
01:18:04,548 --> 01:18:06,992
[SPEAKER_02]: £800 rent per month.

964
01:18:07,012 --> 01:18:10,737
[SPEAKER_02]: It should be more focused on the minimum wage rather than zero hours contract, I think.

965
01:18:10,757 --> 01:18:15,444
[SPEAKER_26]: Okay, Sarah Champion, Labour, zero hours contracts work for this lady, you want to ban them?

966
01:18:15,765 --> 01:18:19,370
[SPEAKER_21]: Yeah, we want to ban exploitative ones because we do not think that that is fair.

967
01:18:19,691 --> 01:18:27,282
[SPEAKER_21]: We think that everybody deserves a proper living wage starting at £10 from the age of 18 because, to be quite honest,

968
01:18:27,262 --> 01:18:31,668
[SPEAKER_21]: Prices of a loaf of bread or a bus fare are the same if you're 18 or 28.

969
01:18:31,728 --> 01:18:50,856
[SPEAKER_21]: It's also taking it back a step, so we want to get apprenticeships, good quality apprenticeships, on a par with university degrees, whereas at the moment they seem to be drifting and there's a stigma associated with apprenticeships which is nonsense because particularly businesses are crying out for well-trained people.

970
01:18:50,836 --> 01:19:00,505
[SPEAKER_21]: What we'll do, which is a really big thing, is we will scrap tuition fees because to come out of a degree with £40,000 debt is crazy.

971
01:19:01,086 --> 01:19:14,819
[SPEAKER_21]: What we'll also be looking at doing is finally getting rid of the gender pay gap because I do not understand why it helps anyone and definitely our economy when a woman is earning on average 18% less than a man doing the same job.

972
01:19:14,979 --> 01:19:20,725
[SPEAKER_21]: We've had Labour brought in legislation around equal pay in 1970 and we're still at an 18% pay gap.

973
01:19:20,705 --> 01:19:26,171
[SPEAKER_21]: What we'll also look at doing is getting a national investment fund.

974
01:19:26,432 --> 01:19:34,061
[SPEAKER_21]: We'll have banks regionally so that small businesses particularly can go to that and grow their business to bring in more employment in the area.

975
01:19:34,401 --> 01:19:40,588
[SPEAKER_21]: But what we're looking for particularly is that sort of high earning jobs rather than just about doing jobs.

976
01:19:40,929 --> 01:19:47,877
[SPEAKER_21]: So 3% of our GDP is actually going to go on research and development because that's what we're seeing is the fastest way to grow our economy.

977
01:19:49,190 --> 01:19:52,636
[SPEAKER_26]: OK, any more questions here about jobs?

978
01:19:52,656 --> 01:19:53,037
[SPEAKER_26]: Hello?

979
01:19:53,518 --> 01:19:55,381
[SPEAKER_04]: Just a quick one to Sarah, sorry for following on that point.

980
01:19:55,581 --> 01:19:55,842
[SPEAKER_04]: Go on.

981
01:19:55,862 --> 01:20:06,060
[SPEAKER_04]: You mentioned it being crazy that students are coming out 2021, whatever it be, with £30,000, £40,000, whatever, £1,000 worth of debt, Labour in power between 1997 and 2010.

982
01:20:06,380 --> 01:20:10,548
[SPEAKER_04]: If it was so crazy to come up with such enormous amounts of debt, why didn't you make the change then?

983
01:20:10,668 --> 01:20:11,890
[SPEAKER_04]: Why are you waiting until now?

984
01:20:12,106 --> 01:20:15,573
[SPEAKER_21]: Well, we brought in £1,000 as opposed to £9,000.

985
01:20:15,893 --> 01:20:20,582
[SPEAKER_21]: I think there's a big difference between a contribution and £9,000.

986
01:20:20,723 --> 01:20:22,666
[SPEAKER_09]: You travelled it though.

987
01:20:22,686 --> 01:20:24,149
[SPEAKER_09]: Brian's right, you travelled it.

988
01:20:24,169 --> 01:20:25,672
[SPEAKER_09]: OK, let's stop about travelling.

989
01:20:25,692 --> 01:20:30,922
[SPEAKER_04]: In terms of your policy, you want to go to completely free.

990
01:20:30,942 --> 01:20:33,928
[SPEAKER_04]: If that was your ideology now,

991
01:20:33,908 --> 01:20:35,650
[SPEAKER_04]: Why has it changed 10 years ago?

992
01:20:35,690 --> 01:20:42,436
[SPEAKER_04]: Back in, let's say, 2007, for example, you still had 3,000 pounds, roughly, tuition fees and maintenance fees.

993
01:20:42,756 --> 01:20:49,883
[SPEAKER_04]: If you're so against students having debt, why 10 years ago, or when you were last in power, why didn't you abolish it then?

994
01:20:49,903 --> 01:20:52,485
[SPEAKER_21]: Perhaps because it's been 10 years since we've seen how it works in Scotland.

995
01:20:52,606 --> 01:20:54,047
[SPEAKER_21]: I've only been here four years.

996
01:20:54,567 --> 01:20:58,191
[SPEAKER_21]: And what we're doing now is looking at what changes we need for the future.

997
01:20:58,671 --> 01:21:00,973
[SPEAKER_21]: I'm good, but I can't change history, I'm afraid.

998
01:21:00,993 --> 01:21:02,915
[SPEAKER_21]: OK, I think it's time to get a reality check.

999
01:21:02,935 --> 01:21:03,696
[SPEAKER_26]: Jonathan?

1000
01:21:03,676 --> 01:21:04,557
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm glad you said that, Tina.

1001
01:21:05,178 --> 01:21:10,264
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, just going back to your point about McDonald's asking people on zero-hours contracts if they want to transfer, they did.

1002
01:21:10,565 --> 01:21:16,853
[SPEAKER_05]: And as with a lot of other corporate employers, they do find, big employers, they do find that zero-hours contracts work for a lot of people.

1003
01:21:16,893 --> 01:21:25,043
[SPEAKER_05]: But let's remember, those are big multinational companies concerned about their corporate image and may play by the rules that other smaller employers might seek to get round.

1004
01:21:25,023 --> 01:21:33,602
[SPEAKER_05]: But I think it's worth highlighting really the difference that there is between the National Living Wage, as it's been called since April this year, we've heard a lot about, £7.50 an hour for over-25s.

1005
01:21:33,662 --> 01:21:37,069
[SPEAKER_05]: If you're under 25, you can expect to earn a lot less.

1006
01:21:37,430 --> 01:21:45,327
[SPEAKER_05]: Anything between £7.50 and down to £3.50 an hour, which if you're an apprentice like you, an apprenticeship, you're more than likely to get.

1007
01:21:45,307 --> 01:21:50,613
[SPEAKER_05]: So under-25s really are at a disadvantage when it comes to earning a minimum wage.

1008
01:21:50,893 --> 01:22:05,108
[SPEAKER_05]: And just to give you an idea of how many people are on it, KPMG, the global accounting firm, looked at this back in 2006 and found out that just over 20% of people in the UK were paid less than the voluntary living wage, which is £8.45 outside of London.

1009
01:22:05,248 --> 01:22:05,989
[SPEAKER_26]: OK, thank you.

1010
01:22:06,009 --> 01:22:09,373
[SPEAKER_26]: We don't have much time left, but I know a lot of you want to talk about Brexit.

1011
01:22:09,453 --> 01:22:10,774
[SPEAKER_26]: Hello, what's your name?

1012
01:22:11,125 --> 01:22:13,448
[SPEAKER_01]: My name is Rico Smith and I'm 18 years old.

1013
01:22:13,468 --> 01:22:16,993
[SPEAKER_01]: 17.4 million people voted to leave the European Union last year.

1014
01:22:17,975 --> 01:22:22,221
[SPEAKER_01]: March this year, Theresa May triggered Article 50, taking a stance of a hard Brexit.

1015
01:22:22,762 --> 01:22:23,863
[SPEAKER_01]: Can the woman be trusted?

1016
01:22:24,184 --> 01:22:29,271
[SPEAKER_01]: I want to know from the politicians who can truly deliver a Brexit that is a hard Brexit.

1017
01:22:29,291 --> 01:22:32,155
[SPEAKER_26]: Nadeem Zahawi, can Theresa May be trusted with Brexit?

1018
01:22:32,540 --> 01:22:33,461
[SPEAKER_09]: Yes, you can.

1019
01:22:33,481 --> 01:22:37,227
[SPEAKER_09]: I don't think there's a thing as a hard Brexit or a soft Brexit.

1020
01:22:37,247 --> 01:22:38,349
[SPEAKER_09]: I think it's a good Brexit.

1021
01:22:38,389 --> 01:22:40,592
[SPEAKER_09]: And what Theresa May needs is a mandate.

1022
01:22:40,612 --> 01:22:41,594
[SPEAKER_26]: It's all very basic, though.

1023
01:22:41,614 --> 01:22:44,839
[SPEAKER_26]: We keep hearing hard Brexit, soft Brexit, good deal, bad deal.

1024
01:22:44,859 --> 01:22:45,660
[SPEAKER_26]: It's pretty basic.

1025
01:22:45,680 --> 01:22:46,642
[SPEAKER_26]: What does it actually mean?

1026
01:22:46,722 --> 01:22:51,409
[SPEAKER_09]: What it means is Theresa set out 12 points.

1027
01:22:51,389 --> 01:22:52,411
[SPEAKER_09]: for the negotiations.

1028
01:22:52,431 --> 01:22:55,458
[SPEAKER_09]: He gave a very important speech at Lancaster House a few months ago.

1029
01:22:55,498 --> 01:23:02,614
[SPEAKER_09]: So controlling our borders, making sure that we have the best trade deal possible with our European partners.

1030
01:23:02,674 --> 01:23:03,676
[SPEAKER_09]: We remain European.

1031
01:23:04,257 --> 01:23:06,723
[SPEAKER_09]: We're just coming out of the EU institutions.

1032
01:23:06,743 --> 01:23:11,473
[SPEAKER_26]: OK. You have to keep it brief because we don't have much time left and we need to get round all of the parties to be fair.

1033
01:23:11,453 --> 01:23:16,764
[SPEAKER_09]: The important thing is making sure we've got a trade deal that works for the UK and for Europe.

1034
01:23:17,245 --> 01:23:20,512
[SPEAKER_09]: We cooperate and make sure that we deliver defence and security for Europe.

1035
01:23:21,013 --> 01:23:25,202
[SPEAKER_09]: And we have 140,000 workers, for example, in our NHS who are European.

1036
01:23:25,222 --> 01:23:28,028
[SPEAKER_09]: We've got to secure them and Brits living in Europe.

1037
01:23:28,008 --> 01:23:33,197
[SPEAKER_21]: Labour is very clear that we want to maintain an incredibly strong partnership with Europe.

1038
01:23:33,237 --> 01:23:41,592
[SPEAKER_21]: We're very aware that the terms of that are going to be changing, but we cannot be going into this all bluster, throwing the baby out with the bathwater.

1039
01:23:41,792 --> 01:23:51,028
[SPEAKER_21]: What we need to be looking at is workers' rights, environmental protections and security, as well as forming a really strong trading relationship.

1040
01:23:51,008 --> 01:23:53,231
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, to the gentleman there, you're absolutely right.

1041
01:23:53,292 --> 01:23:57,218
[SPEAKER_10]: We do need to get out, and we do need to get out in a timely fashion.

1042
01:23:57,638 --> 01:24:09,196
[SPEAKER_10]: What I do worry about Theresa May's speech, some of it was good, but she seemed to indicate that we might have transition arrangements in many, many areas for an unlimited and unspecified number of years.

1043
01:24:09,517 --> 01:24:10,719
[SPEAKER_10]: And people voted to come out.

1044
01:24:10,999 --> 01:24:12,361
[SPEAKER_10]: We want our fishing waters back.

1045
01:24:12,581 --> 01:24:13,823
[SPEAKER_10]: We want to control our borders.

1046
01:24:14,084 --> 01:24:19,412
[SPEAKER_10]: We want to come out of the single market, and we want to do it in as quick a time as possible.

1047
01:24:19,392 --> 01:24:21,196
[SPEAKER_26]: Yeah, quick as time as possible, bringing the key thing.

1048
01:24:21,237 --> 01:24:22,635
[SPEAKER_26]: Brian Paddock, Liberal Democrats.

1049
01:24:22,767 --> 01:24:27,173
[SPEAKER_06]: What we say is, we don't know what the final deal is going to be.

1050
01:24:27,634 --> 01:24:35,685
[SPEAKER_06]: And who is it, once we know what the final deal is, who is it who should decide whether that is an acceptable deal or not?

1051
01:24:36,025 --> 01:24:39,350
[SPEAKER_06]: Should it be politicians or should it be you?

1052
01:24:39,410 --> 01:24:41,513
[SPEAKER_06]: And we think you should decide.

1053
01:24:41,913 --> 01:24:50,665
[SPEAKER_06]: We think that we should stay in the single market because that's going to be best for the economy, it's going to be best for jobs, and it's going to be, if you want to go and

1054
01:24:50,645 --> 01:24:51,406
[SPEAKER_06]: Move to Europe.

1055
01:24:51,686 --> 01:24:57,331
[SPEAKER_06]: If you want to go and work there, if you want to fall in love with somebody from the European Union, then you have got to have free movement.

1056
01:24:57,391 --> 01:24:58,572
[SPEAKER_06]: And that's what we stand for.

1057
01:24:58,592 --> 01:24:59,293
[SPEAKER_30]: That's where we'll leave it.

1058
01:24:59,313 --> 01:25:00,374
[SPEAKER_30]: Kate Forbes, SNP.

1059
01:25:00,414 --> 01:25:04,077
[SPEAKER_30]: So we respect across the UK that a majority voted to leave the EU.

1060
01:25:04,097 --> 01:25:06,460
[SPEAKER_30]: But in Scotland, 62% voted to remain.

1061
01:25:06,860 --> 01:25:18,711
[SPEAKER_30]: And so over the last year, Nicola Sturgeon put forward some compromise solutions for what, in a way that would recognise the majority vote to leave, but also Scotland's position in voting to remain.

1062
01:25:18,691 --> 01:25:22,176
[SPEAKER_30]: All those proposals and discussions have been soundly rejected.

1063
01:25:22,557 --> 01:25:37,821
[SPEAKER_30]: And so we're now in a position of saying, well, once we know the deal, whenever that might be over the next two years, we will give people in Scotland the opportunity to choose between a hard Brexit that doesn't take into account Scotland's interests and independence in the EU.

1064
01:25:37,901 --> 01:25:39,383
[SPEAKER_30]: Jonathan Bartley, the Green Party.

1065
01:25:39,363 --> 01:25:41,305
[SPEAKER_07]: We want a ratification referendum.

1066
01:25:41,365 --> 01:25:45,509
[SPEAKER_07]: We will fight to maintain environmental rights, workers' rights, freedom of movement.

1067
01:25:45,569 --> 01:25:51,734
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm absolutely passionate about maintaining freedom of movement and the next generation having those benefits which I had in my generation.

1068
01:25:51,754 --> 01:25:57,659
[SPEAKER_07]: It's not fair to shortchange the next generation and take away those freedoms, those rights that we've enjoyed.

1069
01:25:57,700 --> 01:26:00,382
[SPEAKER_07]: This generation is getting shortchanged enough as it is.

1070
01:26:00,402 --> 01:26:02,984
[SPEAKER_07]: It's getting saddled with private debt from the public sector.

1071
01:26:03,665 --> 01:26:05,346
[SPEAKER_07]: It's not getting the jobs that we want.

1072
01:26:05,366 --> 01:26:09,370
[SPEAKER_07]: It's not getting the opportunities we should have a say for them in the final district.

1073
01:26:09,350 --> 01:26:14,495
[SPEAKER_22]: I think you say there's no such thing as a hard Brexit.

1074
01:26:14,555 --> 01:26:25,406
[SPEAKER_22]: Wales has 200,000 jobs connected to tariff-free trading with the single market and we are net beneficiaries from the EU because in Wales we have some of the poorest areas in Europe when we're looking at GDP.

1075
01:26:25,667 --> 01:26:38,800
[SPEAKER_22]: So a good deal with the European Union is absolutely crucial for the people of Wales and what Plaid Cymru want is a mandate from the people of Wales to go to Westminster to put Wales on the political agenda and make sure that our voice is heard in those negotiations.

1076
01:26:38,780 --> 01:26:41,845
[SPEAKER_22]: OK, let's get a few more closing thoughts on Brexit from you guys.

1077
01:26:41,865 --> 01:26:42,186
[SPEAKER_26]: Hello.

1078
01:26:42,686 --> 01:26:43,608
[SPEAKER_11]: Hi, my name's Shakti.

1079
01:26:44,630 --> 01:26:46,993
[SPEAKER_11]: Brexit has a significant impact in terms of education.

1080
01:26:47,013 --> 01:26:51,581
[SPEAKER_11]: I want to know from the parties in terms of, like, how will they address that and support education?

1081
01:26:52,302 --> 01:26:55,888
[SPEAKER_11]: Because Brexit makes it more difficult to utilise resources internationally.

1082
01:26:56,829 --> 01:27:02,439
[SPEAKER_11]: Students considering PhDs are gaining funding from international institutes but still studying in the UK.

1083
01:27:02,639 --> 01:27:04,602
[SPEAKER_26]: How do you feel about Brexit?

1084
01:27:04,582 --> 01:27:08,527
[SPEAKER_13]: I'd just like to return to the point that Sarah Champion made, which is fantastic, about workers' rights.

1085
01:27:09,368 --> 01:27:19,280
[SPEAKER_13]: Going forward with negotiations about the Human Rights Bill, that's something that LGBT persons in our society look towards, for the same rights to work, live and marry those that we love.

1086
01:27:19,781 --> 01:27:29,052
[SPEAKER_13]: Heading forward, I want it to be really important to both parties, in whatever negotiations they do, that those rights must be affirmed and upheld in a society that is often changing.

1087
01:27:29,072 --> 01:27:32,697
[SPEAKER_26]: Thank you very much, and let's get a few closing comments also from online.

1088
01:27:32,717 --> 01:27:32,817
Nick?

1089
01:27:32,797 --> 01:27:38,773
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes, Brexit is something that whoever's in charge come the end of the week will have to deal with almost straight away.

1090
01:27:39,073 --> 01:27:41,600
[SPEAKER_08]: But as we've seen tonight, there are lots of different views still.

1091
01:27:42,121 --> 01:27:42,783
[SPEAKER_08]: Here's a couple.

1092
01:27:43,064 --> 01:27:49,641
[SPEAKER_08]: James says, when will people realise this election is for the best Brexit, not for a future government?

1093
01:27:49,621 --> 01:27:53,689
[SPEAKER_08]: And then Richard, the 48% of us who voted to remain are being forgotten.

1094
01:27:54,029 --> 01:27:55,993
[SPEAKER_08]: The whole referendum was a mess.

1095
01:27:56,474 --> 01:28:06,012
[SPEAKER_08]: Now I for one think tonight's debate has been quite well behaved, but Craig, with a parting thought for us, what about a new campaigning rule where you can't bad mouth other parties?

1096
01:28:06,513 --> 01:28:08,296
[SPEAKER_08]: The insults are irrelevant.

1097
01:28:08,576 --> 01:28:09,418
[SPEAKER_08]: Back to you, Tina.

1098
01:28:09,668 --> 01:28:10,610
[SPEAKER_26]: Thank you very much, Nick.

1099
01:28:10,630 --> 01:28:14,115
[SPEAKER_26]: So this has been Newsbeat with the final debate.

1100
01:28:14,155 --> 01:28:18,503
[SPEAKER_26]: A big thank you to our guests tonight and to all of the audience here in Manchester.

1101
01:28:18,683 --> 01:28:26,937
[SPEAKER_26]: If there is anything that you still want to get your head around in the last day before the election, then you should really do a search for BBC Reality Check.

1102
01:28:26,957 --> 01:28:31,845
[SPEAKER_26]: But from all of us here in Manchester, good night.

1103
01:28:35,403 --> 01:28:46,493
All my life...

